{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"dfb776ed-dc26-44ff-910c-a44d14722076","content":"`SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` tells the layout not to inset for safe areas, but the app window itself still isn't drawing behind the system bars. You need **both**:\n\n1. **Enable edge-to-edge rendering** at the window/platform level so the app draws behind the status and navigation bars.\n2. **Remove safe area insets** so the layout doesn't add padding back.\n\n**Android** — In `MainActivity.cs`:\n```csharp\nusing AndroidX.Core.View;\n\nprotected override void OnCreate(Bundle? savedInstanceState)\n{\n    base.OnCreate(savedInstanceState);\n    WindowCompat.SetDecorFitsSystemWindows(Window, false);\n    Window.SetStatusBarColor(Android.Graphics.Color.Transparent);\n    Window.SetNavigationBarColor(Android.Graphics.Color.Transparent);\n}\n```\n\n**iOS** — Add the platform-specific property on your page:\n```xml\n<ContentPage xmlns:ios=\"clr-namespace:Microsoft.Maui.Controls.PlatformConfiguration.iOSSpecific;\n             assembly=Microsoft.Maui.Controls\"\n             ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"False\"\n             SafeAreaEdges=\"None\">\n    <Image Source=\"photo.jpg\" Aspect=\"AspectFill\" />\n</ContentPage>\n```\n\n**Key point:** `SafeAreaEdges` controls layout padding; `SetDecorFitsSystemWindows(false)` (Android) and `UseSafeArea=\"False\"` (iOS) control whether the window extends behind system chrome. You need both layers configured.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"b996f673-4bca-4999-af58-ab53c2c403fd","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about making content go edge-to-edge in a .NET MAUI app, going behind the status bar and navigation bar. They've tried `SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` but still have padding.\n\nThis is a .NET MAUI question about ignoring safe areas for full-screen/edge-to-edge content. Let me think about what I know:\n\nIn .NET MAUI, to make content go edge-to-edge (behind status bar and navigation bar), you typically need to:\n\n1. Set the page to ignore safe areas\n2. On iOS, you need to handle the safe area insets\n\n\n3. On Android, you need to handle the system bars\n\nThe `SafeAreaEdges` property isn't a standard .NET MAUI property I'm familiar with. I'm thinking about what's available in the current .NET MAUI versions. On iOS, you'd use the platform-specific property `ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"false\"`, and on Android, you typically need to configure the window to extend edge-to-edge behind the system bars.\n\nThe user mentions `SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` on ContentPage, which sounds like it could be a newer unified API, but I'm not confident about the exact .NET 10 MAUI APIs for this. The core challenge is that even with safe area handling configured, there might be additional platform-specific setup needed to truly go edge-to-edge.\n\nOn Android specifically, the app needs to enable edge-to-edge mode in addition to handling safe area insets, especially since Android 15+ enforces this by default. On iOS, `UseSafeArea=\"false\"` handles the safe area padding. The user's `SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` might only be addressing the inset padding without actually making the content draw behind the system bars, so they likely need to enable edge-to-edge mode on Android as well. to distinguish between safe area padding and actually rendering behind the system bars—they're separate concerns. On Android, I need to set the window to not fit system windows and make the status and navigation bars transparent. There's platform-specific code for this, though .NET 10 might have newer APIs available.\n\nSetting up edge-to-edge rendering...","outputTokens":1593,"requestId":"142A:315D54:309FEF:37C672:6A03CF9A"},"id":"a612a9b3-e318-43e0-b8b0-33c74ed7205d","timestamp":"2026-05-13T01:11:23.737Z","parentId":"638fbdd0-d35e-42ef-acd6-a9abae945d9c"}
